The Mercurial "narrow" extension (included since Hg 4.6) which supports cloning of just some directories within the repository.

These operations can be desirable for reasons including:

* You&#x27;re working on just one part of a large project, so a narrow clone is faster and takes less space than a full clone
* Particularly on Windows, which by default has case-insensitive file naming, you&#x27;re working with a repository that includes some files with case collisions (same name except upper vs. lower-case characters). That often happens when one part of the project is built under Linux and another part under Windows.

A command like:

{code}
#!bash

hg clone --narrow --exclude &#x27;linux&#x27; ssh://hg@bitbucket.org/name_of_repository
{code}

currently results in the error message "abort: server does not support narrow clones".

h1. General Description
For any file where both HTML and CSS are present (But specifically intended for &#x27;component&#x27; files like .vue), when viewing a pull-request the HTML is generally looked at before the CSS. This feature would allow the user to hover their mouse over the name of a CSS class (For example class="myClass") and a tooltip / popover would display the CSS rules for that class which is declared elsewhere on the page.

This would make component PRs involve a lot less scrolling, and would be significantly more user friendly.

h1. Specifically
When viewing a Pull Request, if the user hovers on the text:

{code}
#!HTML

class="{CLASS_NAME}"
{code}

or

{code}
#!HTML

class=&#x27;{CLASS_NAME}&#x27;
{code}

where on the same page exists the code:

{code}
#!css

.{CLASS_NAME} {
  a: b;
  c: d;
  e: f;
}
{code}

where {CLASS_NAME} is any valid CSS classname, a, c, and e, and css rules and b, d, and f are values\\
the software will show a tooltip or popover that displays:

{code}
#!css

.{CLASS_NAME} {
  a: b;
  c: d;
  e: f;
}
{code}

Similar to [this endpoint|https://developer.atlassian.com/bitbucket/api/2/reference/resource/pullrequests/%257Btarget_user%257D] however instead of all pull requests authored by {target_user} it would return all pull requests that {target_user} is a reviewer on. I&#x27;m not sure if this endpoint already exists. I tried searching the docs and these issues but couldn&#x27;t find anything. This would prevent me from needing to manually provide each repo then querying each repo&#x27;s pullrequest endpoint and filtering (which should also reduce some server load as it would only be one request instead of multiple).

Perhaps an endpoint like:

{code}
/2.0/pullrequests/{target_user}/reviewer
{code}

or a filter query parameter like

{code}
/2.0/pullrequests/{target_user}?kind=reviewer
{code}

Or something similar.

